<HEADLINE>
FT  15 AUG 94 / Rival companies seek to buy remains of Canadian insurer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANET MCFARLAND and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Rival North American insurance companies are already expressing interest in
buying elements of Confederation Life Insurance, Canada's fourth-largest
insurer, which was seized by financial regulators last week.
Their reaction comes against a background of concern about the longer-term
damage Confed's collapse will inflict on Canada's insurance market. With
assets of CDollars 19.2bn (Pounds 8.9bn), Confed is the largest insurance
company to fail in North America.
Ms Suzanne Labarge, Canada's acting superintendent of financial
institutions, said regulators would move quickly to sell assets before their
value was eroded.
Mr Paul Cantor, Confed chief executive, said negotiations announced last
week to sell the company's British operation to a financial services group
were continuing, and the sale should be announced 'very soon'.
The UK arm provides insurance to 250,000 policyholders and is one of the
biggest pooled pension providers to medium-sized British companies.
It is believed the buyer may be a Canadian insurer with UK operations,
suggesting Sun Life as a possible bidder because it has cash for
acquisitions.
The UK operation is estimated to be worth more than CDollars 350m, but Mr
Cantor has acknowledged that it will be much harder now to sell assets for
the price they would have realised before the regulators intervened.
Insurers that have expressed a public interest in acquiring parts of Confed
include Great-West Life Assurance, North American Life Assurance and Aetna
Canada.
Canadian regulators took control of 123-year-old Confed last Thursday to
prevent a run on its policies and deposits after the failure of long-running
efforts to bail it out. The mutual insurer had suffered a rapidly eroding
capital base leaving it unable to meet liabilities.
The regulators will apply today for a court order to wind up the company and
will order accountancy firm Peat Marwick Thorne, which is managing the
company for the regulator, to sell as many of Confed's assets as possible to
other insurers.
But the cheap buying opportunities for rival companies will be eclipsed by
the severe damage the Canadian industry will suffer for years, according to
the country's insurance officials.
The fund protecting policyholders, known as CompCorp, is fully
industry-sponsored, and analysts predict companies will be overburdened by
the contributions they will have to make.
</TEXT>
