<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 94 / Trade victory for embattled Clinton: Deal 'agreed' on
fast-track negotiating ability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The embattled White House yesterday scored a much needed success when it
reached agreement with House Republicans on a new trade negotiating
authority allowing it to pursue new trade pacts in Latin American and Asia.
The 'fast-track' negotiating authority enables the executive branch to
negotiate trade agreements which Congress promises not to amend. It is seen
as essential to President Clinton's credibility as he seeks trade
liberalisation pacts beyond the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
Uruguay Round and the North American Free Trade Agreement.
A senior administration official said last night that the two sides had also
resolved a big stumbling block to passage of the Uruguay Trade Round
implementing legislation by agreeing a Dollars 12bn-Dollars 14bn financing
package to compensate for lost tariff revenues. Under congressional budget
deficit reduction rules, all legislation which incurs costs must be paid for
when it is approved.
The fast-track authority will be included in the House ways and means
committee implementing legislation. The Senate finance committee has refused
to include it, but when the two committees meet to resolve their
differences, perhaps as early as next week, the administration believes the
Senate conferees will accept the deal worked out.
The senior official refused to give details of the deal. It is understood,
however, that the administration has been forced to give up efforts to
attach a provision which included environment and labour rules as
negotiating objectives. However, there is no provision actually prohibiting
such negotiations.
Many Democrats have said they will oppose granting a fast-track authority
without worker and environment rules. But the senior official said he
believed there would be majorities in both houses to pass the implementing
fast track legislation.
Fears have been expressed on the left and right of both parties that by
joining the World Trade Organisation, which will supersede Gatt, the US will
be giving up some of its sovereignty.
The administration is said to have agreed a provision allowing Congress to
vote to withdraw from the WTO at some time in the future. Analysts say this
is fairly meaningless, since the US constitution gives Congress authority
over trade, and it could withdraw from anything it wants.
The official said Mr Clinton's loss on the crime bill earlier this week
would help, rather than hurt the Uruguay Round vote. 'The president is going
to take the issue to the country. He will gain tremendous support and we
will have a crime bill,' the official said. 'It will help us. It will show
that this president has the ability to turn issues around.'
</TEXT>
