<HEADLINE>
FT  13 AUG 94 / Finance and the Family: Last of the banks - The week ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors will be watching for shocks at HSBC Holdings as it concludes the
interim results season for UK banks. Shares have already fallen sharply this
year on worries over Asia-Pacific growth, and its exposure to financial
markets trading.
On Monday, the bank, now the parent of Midland bank, is expected to report
pre-tax profits of about Pounds 1.3bn, compared with Pounds 1.17bn. Earnings
per share are expected to rise by 5 per cent to about 34p and the dividend
to be increased 14 per cent to 8p.
Argos, the catalogue retailer, is forecast on Monday to announce an increase
in interim pre-tax profits from Pounds 13.2m to about Pounds 15m. The
company said at its annual meeting that like-for-like sales - which exclude
new stores - had increased 9 per cent in the first four months of the year,
although they had slowed since then. Margins are thought to have held
steady.
Kalon, the paints group, is expected to report increased first-half profits
of Pounds 10m (Pounds 8.73m) on Tuesday following improved contributions
from Novodec - the French paint maker acquired for Pounds 22m last year -
and Vallance, the specialist products business which cost Pounds 6.2m. It
has also enjoyed some organic growth in the trade paints business, and is
likely to recommend a 1.5p (1.3p) interim dividend.
Continued rate competition in the US insurance market could hold back profit
growth at Sedgwick, the insurance broker, which reports its interim results
on Tuesday. Analysts expect pre-tax profits for the six months to be between
Pounds 55m and Pounds 64m, against Pounds 54.1m.
Britannic Assurance, the life insurance company, will on Wednesday announce
its results for the first half of the year. Like other life companies, it is
not required to release interim profits figures, so attention will focus on
the interim dividend.
Last summer, the interim rose to 3.85p, against 3.433p. Analysts' forecasts
for the interim dividend this year are round 4.2p or 4.3p - an increase of 9
or 10 per cent.
BICC, the cables and construction company, reports its interim results on
Wednesday. The results should show a further improvement in the group's main
UK and US cable markets with pre-tax profits expected to nudge above Pounds
60m for the six months to the end of June, against a re-stated Pounds 50m.
Earnings should be sufficient to cover a maintained dividend but increased
payments to shareholders are some way off.
</TEXT>
