<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Zaire's ministers 'paid Dollars 14,500 a month'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHELA WRONG OF REUTERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINSHASA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Zaire's previous government paid its ministers salaries of Dollars 12,500 to
Dollars 14,500 a month despite a financial crisis and grinding poverty, a
report ordered by Mr Kengo Wa Dondo, the new prime minister, says.
The salaries would be generous in a western country but in Zaire, where a
government clerical worker earns 17,000 zaires (Dollars 12) a month and an
ordinary soldier gets 5,000 zaires, they are stratospheric.
The report, passed to Reuters and confirmed by ex-ministers, also says
paymasters in the government of former prime minister, Mr Faustin Birindwa,
actually drew between two and three times the authorised salaries from the
Bank of Zaire and pocketed the difference before paying the cabinet.
Mr Kengo, appointed in June to head a government of national unity, has
promised to put an end to the corrupt practices that dogged past
administrations and to halt Zaire's financial collapse.
In Zaire, state office is traditionally viewed as an opportunity for
amassing personal wealth, a fact President Mobutu Sese Seko has publicly
acknowledged.
According to the document, dated July 26 and compiled by a former member of
Mr Birindwa's cabinet, deputy ministers were paid Dollars 12,500 a month,
ministers Dollars 13,500 and deputy prime ministers Dollars 14,500. No
figure is given for Birindwa.
The payments were awarded at a time when Zaire was nursing foreign debts of
Dollars 9.5bn and was shortly to have its voting rights at the International
Monetary Fund suspended for non-payment of arrears. Local economists
estimate the budget deficit for the first six months of 1994 at around
Dollars 60m.
Former members of Mr Birindwa's government confirmed the details given in
the report on Thursday, but said that during its 14 months in office only
nine pay cheques were delivered.
They also revealed how the inner circle in charge of payments made further
profits. Salaries were paid in zaires at an exchange rate chosen arbitrarily
by Mr Birindwa, which was well below the market level, often halving the
final dollar value.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ZRZ  Zaire, Africa.
</CN>
