<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Sellafield nears US military deal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Nitric acid contaminated with uranium from a US atomic weapons plant may be
reprocessed at Sellafield, Cumbria. Between 15 and 20 shipments a year are
proposed, together worth about Dollars 500m (Pounds 325m) to British Nuclear
Fuels.
The material would come from a closed US military reprocessing plant that is
being cleaned up under a programme to deal with sites contaminated by the
military.
UK government policy is that countries should handle their own waste and not
send it overseas. But BNFL said last night the material was not waste.
Uranium was regularly imported into the UK to make fuel for power stations.
'The import of uranium in the acid is no different as the acid will be
re-used and the separated uranium can also be re-used.'
The purified uranium would be owned by the US and would be stored at
Capenhurst, Cheshire
</TEXT>
