<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Severn Trent in urgent review of dangerous chemicals storage
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Severn Trent Water is to carry out an urgent review of the storage of
hazardous chemicals near rivers following a pollution incident earlier this
year.
The review is one of 28 recommendations in a report commissioned by Severn
Trent after organic chemicals entered the River Severn after their discharge
into a sewer in Shropshire.
Up to 120,000 homes in the Worcester area were unable to use tap water for
more than two days in April. Severn Trent has paid out nearly Pounds 1m
compensation to residents who had to queue at water tankers.
The report, by Professor Ken Ives, identifies 'serious weaknesses' in the
system at the time of the incident. As criminal proceedings are pending, the
report contains no findings or recommendations concerning the origin of the
pollution.
The discharge passed undetected through a sewage treatment works at Wem and
entered the Severn through two small tributaries.
Four days later consumers started complaining of an unpleasant taste. It
took 16 hours from the first complaint to trace the alleged source.
Prof Ives calls for improved detection procedures. He says it is 'a matter
of great concern' that such odourless chemicals could pass through a sewage
treatment works and be discharged into an important supply river.
The report adds that the response to complaints was rapid and efficient
although some sections of the public, particularly the elderly and those
living alone, were not alerted quickly enough.
Although the spill was not life-threatening, the report says the incident
has highlighted the urgent need for a national review of the system of
licensing the storage of chemicals, especially near vulnerable water
courses.
The report calls on Severn Trent and the National Rivers Authority to
establish a database of potential sources of river pollution and calls for
closer collaboration between the water service companies and the NRA over
river pollution incidents.
Mr Victor Cocker, Severn Trent managing director, said all recommendations
would be acted on, and some had already been implemented.
</TEXT>
