<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Clinton's anti-crime drive suffers setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The House of Representatives dealt a heavy blow to President Bill Clinton
yesterday, defeating a Dollars 33.2bn (Pounds 21.4bn) multi-faceted
anti-crime package for which the president had personally lobbied.
Voting 225 to 210, the House defeated a procedural rule need to bring the
legislation, known as the crime bill, to the floor. The vote effectively
kills the bill in this form and denies Mr Clinton an anti-crime initiative
he had promised during his 1992 election campaign.
The defeat could undermine the effectiveness of the Clinton presidency;
political analysts said it seemed certain to make life more difficult for
the president in his efforts to get the centrepiece of his legislative
agenda - the healthcare bill - through Congress.
In an unusual twist, the powerful US gun lobby and the influential
Congressional Black Caucus - which normally favours gun control - teamed up
to delay and ultimately defeat the bill.
The gun lobby opposed a ban on 19 types of assault weapons included in the
legislation, while the black caucus was angered that a controversial 'racial
justice provision' had been removed from the bill in the face of stiff
Republican opposition.
The measure would have allowed minority defendants facing the death penalty
to use statistics to challenge capital punishment as racially biased.
Mr Clinton had sent Mr Leon Panetta, his chief of staff, to Capitol Hill
earlier in the day to lobby for passage of the procedural vote. The
president and Vice-President Al Gore had also called several members in an
attempt to secure their support.
Later Mr Clinton, who blamed Republicans for the defeat, accused the House
of 'failing the American people'.
The crime bill would have given local communities grants to hire 100,000
more police and provided billions of dollars over six years for new prisons
and crime prevention programmes.
It would also have instituted harsher penalties for certain crimes, raising
to 60 the number of federal crimes for which US attorneys would be allowed
to seek the death penalty and mandating life sentences for third-time
felons.
</TEXT>
<XX>
