<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Sell-off in bond market fells
Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSOM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
A sell-off in the Treasury market, prompted by rising expectations of an
imminent interest rate increase, and a disastrous 30-year bond auction, left
US share prices lower across the board yesterday, writes Patrick Harverson
in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 15.86 at 3,750.90.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 slipped 1.42 to 458.88, while
the American Stock Exchange composite finished 0.72 off at 443.25 and the
Nasdaq composite unchanged at 728.20. Trading volume on the New York SE
amounted to 275.7m shares.
Although prices opened marginally higher, the market struggled to hold on to
its gains as Treasury prices slipped steadily lower, pushing long-term
interest rates, as measured by the yield on the 30-year government bond,
higher. The decline in bond prices was sparked by a series of economic
releases which were not overly bearish, but were worrying enough to convince
more investors that the Federal Reserve would soon sanction another interest
rate increase to slow down the economy.
The news that led to the sell-off in the bond market was an upward revision
in June retail sales growth, from an originally estimated 0.6 per cent to
0.8 per cent. Analysts said that the robust growth in retail sales, combined
with recent strong jobs growth, made it more likely that the Fed would
tighten monetary policy, probably after next week's meeting of the Federal
Open Market Committee.
Bond prices fell further later in the day after investors shunned the
Treasury's auction of Dollars 11bn new 30-year bonds.
The day's other news - a 0.5 per cent rise in July producer prices and a 0.1
per cent decline in July retail sales - had less of an impact. The bigger
than expected rise in producer prices was ignored because the gain was
attributable almost entirely to higher petrol and coffee prices.
Gap Stores jumped Dollars 4 3/8 to Dollars 41 1/4 in volume of 2.8m shares
after announcing second-quarter earnings per share of 30 cents, up from 20
cents last year and above forecasts.
US Bioscience rose Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 6 1/8 on the American Stock
Exchange after the company's Hexalen drug, which is used in the treatment of
ovarian cancer, was cleared by regulators for marketing in Canada.
On the Nasdaq market, technology stocks were in demand once again: Microsoft
advanced Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 55 1/4 in heavy trading, Intel climbed
Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 60 3/8 and Lotus Development appreciated Dollars 1
to Dollars 41 1/4 .
Neutrogena forged ahead Dollars 4 7/8 to Dollars 26 1/2 after the personal
care products concern said it was in talks with a larger company that could
lead to a takeover of Neutrogena.
Comcast Communications moved up Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 17 1/8 immediately
after the cable television group reported a narrowing in its second-quarter
loss to Dollars 12.8m, from Dollars 17m a year ago, but the shares later
fell back to end unchanged at Dollars 16 3/4 .
Canada
Toronto closed sharply lower after moderate trading as fears of rising
interest rates drove North American markets down.
The TSE 300 composite index dropped 30.4 to 4,174.7 and declining issues
outnumbered advances by 419 to 298 after volume of 60.1m shares valued at
CDollars 651m.
Twelve of the 14 sub-indices weakened, led by mining, off 1.6 per cent.
Industrial products fell 1.3 per cent and financial services shed 1.2 per
cent. The transportation group had the day's biggest rise, 1.0 per cent. The
golds group also closed higher.
Spar Aerospace, down CDollars  3/4 at CDollars 14 1/2 , reported
second-quarter earnings of CDollars 170,000 or 1 cent a share, down sharply
from a year-earlier net of C2.5m or 17 cents a share.
Brazil
Shares retreated by 1.1 per cent in volatile trading in Sao Paulo, dragged
down ahead of the options and futures markets settlements next Monday and
Wednesday.
The Bovespa index of the 56 most-traded shares ended 494 down at 44,638.
Turnover was RDollars 333.4m (Dollars 372.9m).
</TEXT>
