<PROFILE>_AN-EHLDRAFCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940812
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Markets Report: Rate rises hit markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Financial markets yesterday received a rude wake-up call from their summer
torpor as both Sweden and Italy lifted short-term interest rates, writes
Philip Gawith.
The 50 basis-point increase in the Swedish ceiling rate to 8 per cent, and a
similar rise in the Italian discount rate, to 7.5 per cent, raised fears
that the interest rate cycle in Europe may have bottomed.
The rate moves were poorly received by sceptical markets, and both
currencies traded lower. Yesterday afternoon the lira was quoted at a record
low of L1,016.50 against the D-Mark, compared to a London close of L1,005
some 10 minutes before the rate move was announced.
The Swedish krona was quoted in London at SKr4.987 against the D-Mark, off a
low of SKr5, but well below Wednesday's close of SKr4.940.
Events in Europe overshadowed the release of a fairly neutral set of July
PPI and retail sales figures in the US. The dollar, however, weakened
sharply as nervous investors sought refuge from currency turbulence in the
D-Mark.
Yesterday evening the dollar was trading at DM1.5635, more than 2 1/2
pfennigs off the day's high of DM1.5905. In New York it finished at
DM1.5600.
Sterling had a steady day, with weakness against the D-Mark offset by
strength against the dollar. At midday in New York the pound was trading at
Dollars 1.5485, up from Dollars 1.53 earlier, and DM2.4256, down from
DM2.4350.
The interest rate futures markets had a hectic day with heavy volumes
traded, and large price movements. The December short sterling contract saw
more than 50,000 lots traded and was bid yesterday evening at 93.23,
compared to Wednesday's close of 93.43. The December Euromark contract
traded 66,000 lots and was bid at 94.78, compared to the previous close of
94.96.
Sweden's central bank, the Riksbank, said it raised rates as a pre-emptive
strike against inflation. The Bank of Italy, in turn, said rates were lifted
in order to defend the lira.
Markets, however, were equally unimpressed with both motivations and
predicted further currency weakness.
Mr Jeremy Hawkins, chief economist at Bank of America in London, commented:
'The message from the market to big budget deficit governments is that
investors are no longer prepared to invest in their assets unless we see a
big cut in their budget deficit, or a big increase in interest rates. Fifty
basis points is neither here nor there.'
Mr Hawkins said the market's initial response had been so negative that
speculators were now likely to turn their attention to other countries with
fiscal problems, notably Portugal, Greece and Belgium. 'The foreign exchange
market at the moment is now looking at budget deficits more than anything
else.'
Countries with a sounder fiscal position are expected to stay out of the
firing line. Mr Brian Durrant, economist at broker GNI, commented: 'I do not
think German policy will be altered in any shape or form by events we have
seen today.' Indeed, some analysts believe another interest rate cut from
the Bundesbank is likely, possibly as soon as next week when the council
next meets.
Mr Tony Norfield, UK treasury economist at ABN-Amro, noted: 'The issue is
fiscal deficits rather than Swedish monetary policy being a leading
indicator for Europe. But that is certainly how the market is seeing it
now.'
That said, yesterday's rate moves have clearly served as a further catalyst
for bearishness across the board in European interest rate markets.
A common criticism among analysts was that both central banks had
essentially missed the point, which was that markets were worried about
large budget deficits.
Against this background, selling the currency is logical because higher
interest rates promise only to aggravate the economic difficulties these
countries face, and make holding their assets a less palatable prospect.
Some analysts said the central banks' actions could be interpreted as
warning shots across the bows of the politicians, warning them that they had
to cut their budget deficits.
Mr Jouni Kokko, international economist at SG Warburg in London, said high
debt countries might have to accept a degree of exchange rate fluctuation as
the price for interest rate independence.
He predicted that the issue of how high deficit countries would cope with
rising interest rates would prompt further speculation against their
currencies.
The dollar's weakness was attributed more to the search for safety in the
D-Mark rather than in any specific concern about the US currency. Analysts
said that yesterday's data were unlikely to have altered any views of the
likelihood, or not, of a Fed tightening at next week's FOMC meeting.
In the UK money markets, the Bank of England provided late assistance of
Pounds 120m after forecasting a Pounds 350m shortage. Earlier it had
supplied Pounds 200m liquidity at established rates. In the cash markets,
sterling LIBOR firmed on speculation of higher rates to 5 per cent from 5
9/16 per cent.
</TEXT>
