<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / International Bonds: Finland raises CDollars 200m over 10
years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN and LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Amid the turmoil in Europe's government bond markets following interest-rate
tightening in Sweden and Italy, activity in the eurobond market all but
ground to a halt.
The only significant deal of the day was a CDollars 200m issue of 10-year
bonds for the Republic of Finland via joint lead managers Paribas and Swiss
Bank Corporation. The bonds were priced to yield 27.5 basis points over the
Canadian 10-year government benchmark bond at their re-offer price of
99.845.
While the leads reported good demand from the Benelux region and
Switzerland, boosted by the 9.5 per cent coupon, other dealers felt the
issue had been too tightly priced.
'Given the size and the timing of the deal, I think it should have had an
extra 10 basis points' on the spread, said one syndicate manager, adding
that the timing of the deal, amid a raft of US inflation indicators, was
'bizarre.' After the bonds were freed to trade, the spread widened to around
31 basis points.
While more swap-driven Canadian-dollar issues are expected soon, activity is
expected to remain quiet near-term, with most of Europe closed for
Assumption holiday on Monday.
The Hong Kong Housing Society, a non-profit making organisation which
provides affordable homes for Hong Kong people, issued a HKDollars 2bn
floating-rate note for general funding purposes, writes Louise Lucas in Hong
Kong.
The 2 1/2 -year notes, the bulk of which will be placed locally, carry an
interest rate of 0.85 per cent over the three-month Hong Kong interbank
offered rate.
The offering will not be listed on any stock exchange. There is a call
option after two years and three months.
Wardley Capital arranged the issue and HSBC Markets is book-runner.
</TEXT>
