<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / UK Company News: Relationship sours after 26 years - The
Scholes-ABB disagreement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER AND DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The breakdown in relations between Scholes Group, the medium-sized UK maker
of electrical installation equipment, and Asea Brown Boveri, Europe's
largest electrical engineering group, looks at first glance to reflect a
classic mismatch between giant and minnow.
Scholes agreed late last month to a Pounds 96.1m takeover bid from Hanson,
the Anglo-US conglomerate. But on Wednesday it said it was open to higher
offers and revealed that, when the Hanson bid was received, it had reached
an advanced stage of discussion with Felten &amp; Guilleaume of Germany to
replace ABB as technology partner.
ABB has a 4.5 per cent stake in Scholes, and has given an irrevocable
undertaking to accept the Hanson bid. But for Scholes to be seeking to
replace ABB indicates how far relations between the two companies have
deteriorated in the past three years.
Early in 1991, amid much fanfare, they announced the formation of two
important UK joint venture companies, strengthening a relationship that had
begun in 1968 with a licensing agreement. The first, ABB Wylex Sales (51 per
cent owned by the UK company) was to sell the products made by the second,
ABB Wylex Product &amp; Development (51 per cent owned by ABB).
This was an expanded version of a 1980, Scotland-based joint venture
producing high performance miniature circuit breakers. But it would offer a
range of new products supplied by ABB, including protective equipment,
infra-red sensors and emergency lighting systems.
The 'little and large' element of the deal was apparent at the time - ABB's
research and development spending alone was more than 10 times Scholes'
annual turnover. But both sides saw attractions.
For Scholes, the deal was intended to bring protection from the shocks of
the European Single Market. The late Mr Reg Harrington, then chairman and
chief executive, foresaw dramatic changes in a UK market which still had
about 50 installation equipment suppliers, against three or four for each of
the main continental European markets.
With aggressive foreign companies buying into the UK market, he saw a
broader technology relationship with ABB, Europe's largest installation
equipment supplier, as the key to Scholes' survival.
ABB, meanwhile, hoped that access to 1,500 Wylex outlets would enhance its
position in the UK installation equipment market, where it had been less
successful than on the Continent.
The two sides' accounts of the breakdown vary, but at least they agree on
one point - that the relationship was not living up to expectations.
Scholes' talks with F&amp;G show it would be happier working with a company
nearer to its size. But Mr Eric Drewery, chief executive of ABB in the UK,
rejects the notion that the difference in size made failure inevitable.
'ABB is made up of many large and small companies and the relationship was
between Scholes and ABB Stotz-Kontakt in Germany,' he says. 'The big world
of ABB did not impinge on the relationship.'
Instead, he says, 'there was a mixed bag of problems, some small and some
large, which meant we had not got the mileage we expected out of the joint
ventures. We felt that Scholes could have penetrated further with the
technology we supplied'.
Mr Bill Riches, chairman of Scholes, says the two had come to recognise that
their arrangements were not working as envisaged and relations became 'quite
strained'.
One particular flashpoint has been the two-year negotiations for Scholes to
buy Hanson's Crabtree electrical equipment interests.
Mr Riches says that two years ago ABB indicated it would support a Scholes
offer for Crabtree, contribute Pounds 12m to Pounds 15m (increasing its
stake to 10 to 15 per cent) and support the enlarged group with its
technology.
But after BMW's purchase of Rover, he says, ABB decided it would not put new
money into minority interests involving its technology unless it had some
guarantee that it would eventually lead to control. Scholes could not
provide such a guarantee.
Mr Drewery says ABB had little interest in a minority stake in the enlarged
company, and was not in the business of becoming 'a friendly banker' to
Scholes. It likened its position to that of Honda at Rover to explain why it
did not want an enlarged stake in the bigger group.
Due to this impasse, Scholes started looking for another European partner
that would do more than just supply technology, and started talking to F&amp;G.
Mr Riches claims that ABB, seeing the writing on the wall, went to Hanson
with support for a bid for Scholes.
Mr Drewery emphati-cally denies this - as does Hanson - and says the idea of
a bid for Scholes was Hanson's alone.
Mr Riches says that, if a deal with Hanson is not concluded, he is confident
that replacing ABB as Scholes' technology partner would not be contrary to
its interests. F&amp;G would even be better.
ABB, meanwhile, hopes Hanson will succeed. Mr Drewery believes the combined
Crabtree/Scholes business will be more effective in marketing ABB's products
in UK than Scholes was alone.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Scholes Group.
    ABB Asea Brown Boveri.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    CHZ  Switzerland, West Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3613 Switchgear and Switchboard Apparatus.
    P3532 Mining Machinery.
    P3536 Hoists, Cranes and Monorails.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
