<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Philips trebles with help from the World Cup
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   EINDHOVEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Philips, the Dutch electronics group, more than trebled its profits in the
second quarter of 1994, beating even the most optimistic of analysts'
forecasts.
It also predicted a substantial increase in full-year earnings now that it
has begun to feel the effects of economic recovery in some European
countries.
Part of the second-quarter rise was due to higher sales of colour television
sets in the run-up to this summer's soccer World Cup.
Philips' shares jumped to a new 12-month high of Fl 58.50, but fell back
slightly later in the day to close at Fl 57.80, a rise of Fl 1.90.
Philips said: 'We are rather more encouraged with respect to the future than
we were some six months ago.'
Net profit surged to Fl 402m (Pounds 147m), from Fl 117m before
extraordinary items in the second quarter of 1993. First-half net profit
totalled Fl 662m, up from Fl 220m last year.
Turnover advanced 6 per cent in the quarter, pushing first-half turnover up
3 per cent to Fl 27.96bn. Sales volume in the first six months rose by 8 per
cent, easily outstripping an average 2 per cent fall in prices.
'Some of this growth comes from increased sales of televisions, stimulated
by the World Cup, and is probably not sustainable,' said Mr Dudley Eustace,
finance director. The soccer-inspired sales are thought to be the main
reason behind the 14 per cent increase in consumer electronics turnover in
April-June.
Mr Eustace noted that the decline of the dollar, which is negative for
Philips, was another reason why the strong second-quarter and first-half
performances could probably not be matched in the rest of 1994. However, the
company expected 'substantially better' full-year results.
The heavy restructuring of the early 1990s was paying off, enabling the
management to concentrate on 'revitalising' the company. On Wednesday, for
example, it announced a Fl 500m investment in its Dutch semi-conductor
plant, the biggest single investment since the company ran into difficulties
in 1990.
The semi-conductors and components sector saw first-half operating profit
nearly double to Fl 750m. Consumer electronics swung into an operating
profit of Fl 211m from a loss of Fl 113m, helped by a halving of losses at
Grundig in Germany. Communications equipment activities in Germany continued
to suffer from lower investment by the country's telecommunications
authority.
</TEXT>
