<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Thomas Cook buys Barclays' travellers cheques subsidiary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Thomas Cook, the world's second largest supplier of travellers cheques after
American Express, said yesterday it had acquired the third biggest supplier,
Interpayment Services.
Neither side would disclose how much Thomas Cook was paying for the Barclays
Bank subsidiary.
Interpayment is the world's largest issuer of Visa travellers cheques,
generating annual sales of about Dollars 7bn (Pounds 4.5bn) in 145
countries. The deal increases Thomas Cook's share of the Dollars 54bn
travellers cheque market from 17 per cent to 30 per cent.
Thomas Cook is 90 per cent owned by Westdeutsche Landesbank, Germany's third
biggest bank.
Mr Alex Jablonowski, managing director of Barclays Global Services, said
that the sale was part of the bank's strategy of focusing on its core
businesses.
Barclays, which this week announced first-half pre-tax profits of Pounds
1.04bn, would not say what profit the travellers cheque subsidiary had
generated.
Mr Graham Rider, Thomas Cook's managing director of financial services, said
that the deal would enable the company to sell travellers cheques through
many more banks than is possible now.
Thomas Cook's cheques carry its own logo, together with that of MasterCard.
In Europe, the cheques also carry the sign of euro travellers cheque
International (etcI). Mr Rider said many banks around the world would sell
either MasterCard or Visa travellers cheques, but not both.
The acquisition would allow Thomas Cook to sell Visa cheques as well as
MasterCard, he said.
Mr Rider said that the Thomas Cook MasterCard and the Interpayment Visa
brands would continue to operate separately. They would have discrete sales
and marketing strategies but would use the same distribution and processing
facilities.
Barclays said it would continue to sell Visa travellers cheques through its
branches and customers would not notice any change.
The acquisition goes some way to helping Thomas Cook close the gap on
American Express, its traditional travellers cheque rival, which has 44 per
cent of the world market.
A history of Thomas Cook, written with the company's co-operation, concedes
that American Express invented the travellers cheque in 1891.
American Express admits, however, that persuading Thomas Cook's offices
around the world to honour its cheques was a crucial step towards their
wider acceptance.
</TEXT>
