<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / US sets Bosnian Serbs deadline on peace plan: Clinton
threatens to seek lifting of arms embargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and MATTHEW KAMINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton yesterday set a deadline of October 15 for Bosnian
Serb acceptance of an international peace plan or the US would urge the
United Nations Security Council to lift the arms embargo on Bosnia. The
proposal won swift support from France.
As well as putting extra pressure on the Bosnian Serbs the US
administration's purpose appeared to be aimed at heading off congressional
moves to force the president into a unilateral lifting of the arms embargo.
But in this it failed. Shortly after the announcement, the Senate approved
the Clinton-backed proposal 56-44. But it also approved 58-42 a separate
proposal for Congress to order the president to lift US participation in the
embargo on November 15, if there was no peace agreement by then.
In Paris, Mr Alain Juppe, the French foreign minister, said France was
backing Mr Clinton's deadline. If the Serbs had not accepted the peace plan
by then, France would lift the arms embargo, but he warned such a move would
not be good for the people, for UN forces or for peace. The situation of UN
peacekeepers must be clearly defined before the embargo could be lifted so
they were 'not exposed to a generalised war'.
Mr Clinton wrote to Senator Sam Nunn, chairman of the armed services
committee: 'If by October 15 the Bosnian Serbs have not accepted the Contact
Group's proposal of July 6, 1994, it would be my intention to introduce
formally and support a resolution at the UN Security Council to terminate
the arms embargo.'
The Bosnian Serbs have refused to accept a peace map drawn up by the
so-called Contact Group, consisting of the US, the UK, France, Germany and
Russia, which has led the negotiations. The map roughly divides
Bosnia-Hercegovina into equal shares between the Serbs and a Croat-Moslem
federation.
Meanwhile, Russia yesterday called for the lifting of the economic embargo
on Serbia, which has cut links with the Bosnian Serbs. The foreign ministry
said the sanctions are now 'illogical and counterproductive', as Serbia
appears to have kept its word on the blockade.
The president's letter to Senator Nunn states US concerns about the impact
of unilateral action to lift the embargo, according to extracts made
available to the Washington Post. It states that US relations with its
allies would be 'seriously strained', co-operation with Russia put in
jeopardy and the likelihood of US military involvement 'increased, not
decreased'.
The Bosnian army, which would profit most from access to western heavy
weapons, yesterday continued to make advances against Bosnian Serb troops.
In Sarajevo, UN efforts to feed the city blockaded by Bosnian Serbs suffered
another blow when gunfire hit cargo aircraft, forcing the suspension of the
relief airlift. In the city, sniper fire killed an 11-year-old girl.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
    USZ  United States of America.
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
