<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Dishonest directors worsen Russia's debt crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Corrupt factory managers are exacerbating the debt among Russian business
enterprises which is threatening to paralyse the country's economy, a
government report has warned.
The mountain of debt, now estimated at nearly Dollars 15bn (Pounds 9.8bn),
has built up as businesses fail to pay suppliers, creating a knock-on effect
that has left some companies unable to pay their employees.
The debt levels are seen as so dangerous that a government commission was
convened last week to address the problem and is reporting weekly to the
president and prime minister.
The government report, written by Mr Petr Karpov, deputy director of
Russia's Federal Bankruptcy Agency, and based on a detailed financial study
of 15 Russian enterprises, alleges that a small number of corrupt factory
directors are helping to undermine Russia's financial system.
The report names Russian enterprises and accuses some factory directors of
shipping goods without receiving payment, in exchange for kick-backs.
'Immoral business is now a widely spread norm of economic behaviour, because
it is profitable,' the report concludes. It urges the government to curb
these corrupt business practices by forcing loss-making companies into
bankruptcy.
Inter-enterprise debt poses one of today's biggest challenges for the
Russian government and is a test of Moscow's commitment to economic reforms.
The arrears, which have worsened since the Russian government tightened
credit after its spring agreement with the International Monetary Fund, are
affecting even the most sensitive sectors of the Russian economy, including
the nuclear power industry.
Now the government is facing a choice between bailing out factories and
perhaps triggering a new wave of inflation, or taking the political risk of
forcing bankruptcies.
Tangled mesh of corporate debt, Page 2
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RUZ  Russia, East Europe.
</CN>
