<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Arts: Sir Alex Alexander - An appreciation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE CHRISTIE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Alex Alexander, who died on July 25, did more for Glyndebourne's
financial well-being during his period of trusteeship and directorship than
any other individual in this opera company's history of 60 years. He brought
a new dimension to the business of fund-raising and sponsorship and, at the
same time, he instilled a sense of commercialism in the management of
Glyndebourne's operation. His fund-raising efforts obviously benefited
Glyndebourne's artistic endeavours but the commercial policy never came into
fundamental conflict with artistic objectives.
I first met Alex in 1973, following correspondence in which I invited him to
support Glyndebourne Touring Opera - an invitation which was
characteristically not refused. I felt an immediate rapport with him and
this grew into friendship which, within a few months, caused me to think
that he might join our board of trustees. I consulted one of our trustees,
Sir Mark Turner, who expressed some surprise on the grounds that Alex, to
his knowledge, had not shown much interest in the performing arts up to that
point. Two years after Alex's appointment to the Glyndebourne Arts Trust,
Sir Mark commented that the decision to appoint Alex must have been the best
one of my life - a comment with which I have no possible disagreement.
Alex, within a very brief period of trusteeship, joined the board of
Glyndebourne Productions Limited (the organisation which holds executive
responsibility for the Opera Company). He was also appointed chairman of a
finance committee which I brought into existence in the mid-70s at a time of
recession and at a time when box office receipts were unable to keep pace
with inflation. He was hugely active as chairman of this committee and, as a
result, Glyndebourne - despite diminishing box office returns - successfully
met the challenge of inflationary costs. Alex also chaired an appeal in 1983
which raised Pounds 750,000 to help maintain the fabric of the theatre.
It might be expected that his widespread and very effective success in
'robbing Peter' to pay Glyndebourne could have created enemies. Not so in
the case of Alex, whose charm - he had an irresistible smile - and practical
approach beguiled all who came into his fund-raising sights. I know of no
other individual with a better track record for raising funds for the arts.
Glyndebourne was, I believe, the first charitable organisation in the field
of the performing arts to benefit from his genius, but there were others who
got swept into his slipstream - to their great advantage.
His friendship with people was based on a code of ethics, the chief one of
which was unshakeable loyalty. Once a friend of Alex, always a friend -
unless you breached the code. In Marga he had a wife who gave him stalwart
support in his business life and who, more than anyone, inspired his
interest in the arts. We grieve for her and her family.
Sir George Christie is chairman of Glyndebourne Productions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7922 Theatrical Producers and Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
