<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Stock Exchange probes dealings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stock Exchange has launched a review of trading in shares of the 12
regional electricity companies in recent weeks and has questioned several
brokers about transactions which may have involved insider dealing.
Brokers said the Stock Exchange appeared particularly interested in whether
some directors had purchased shares in rival companies.
Share prices soared yesterday after the report showed price controls less
onerous than were thought likely until recently.
The Stock Exchange declined to comment yesterday. But it is understood that
the exchange, as a routine matter, conducts special surveillance of trading
in a company's shares when it knows a price-sensitive statement is about to
be released. Such statements would include profits reports, notice of an
acquisition or disposal, or - in a regulated industry - news of regulatory
changes.
Dealers said that the purchase by an electricity company director of shares
in a rival did not mean that inside information was available. Such a
decision could have been based on detailed knowledge of the industry and its
likely prospects, similar to the information available to industry analysts
at a securities house. However, if the director was privy to information not
available to knowledgeable individuals, and used that information to
purchase shares, insider dealing may have occurred.
ESN Pension Scheme, the company which invests the regional power companies'
pension funds, yesterday said it had stringent rules on the purchase of
electricity company shares by employees. Employees may not buy the shares
except those offered in an initial 'free' offer. If they do buy shares, they
must do so through a broker selected by ESN which reports all transactions
to senior management. Any share purchases must be reported to management.
</TEXT>
