<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Review starts champagne corks popping
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chief executives of most of the regional electricity companies made a
'gentleman's agreement' some time ago that whatever the outcome of the
distribution review they should not accept the regulator's verdict on the
day it was announced. One said: 'We felt it might be a bit unseemly to snap
it up immediately.'
But behind closed doors yesterday the celebrations were well under way - the
champagne corks had started popping as early as Wednesday morning, almost as
soon as the companies had time to digest Prof Littlechild's report.
The City yesterday expected all 12 electricity distribution companies for
England and Wales to follow the lead of East Midlands Electricity, Yorkshire
Electricity and Seeboard and accept the report. The long months of
uncertainty were all but over and, as one analyst put it, 'none of the
companies are in trouble'.
The rises in share prices and the revised forecasts of analysts suggest that
may be an understatement. UBS was expecting the sector to show real dividend
growth of 8 per cent annually until the end of the decade, with real growth
in earnings per share of 6 per cent a year.
Hoare Govett pushed its forecasts for real dividend growth for the sector
from 6 per cent to 8 per cent to the end of the century. SG Warburg
predicted 6.5 per cent. Most houses also expect the companies to be
cash-positive for most of the five-year review period, taking the businesses
as a whole, rather than just the distribution divisions which were the
subject of Prof Littlechild's review.
Analysts differed, however, on which companies had won and lost the most.
The companies that were initially judged to have come out worst were the
three whose allowed price caps Prof Littlechild said should be revised
downwards by 17 per cent. As a result Chester-based Manweb; Swalec, serving
south Wales; and Northern Electric saw relatively low increases in their
share prices.
There were signs, however, of a rethink later in the day. Some analysts
believed that the scope for Manweb and Swalec to cut costs might mean that
they were not as disadvantaged as at first appeared. There was less
enthusiasm for Northern's position.
Manweb also pointed out that the 17 per cent reduction was from the full
prices it could have charged under the existing formula - since Manweb was
not recovering its full entitlement, the effect was a one-off drop in
nominal charges of just 10 per cent.
The chief executive of another company - one of the six which will be
suffering cuts in allowed revenues of 14 per cent - said it was too
simplistic to judge companies simply on the revenue cut being applied to
them. He said: 'You have to take a variety of factors into account including
the size of the existing price cap, the capital-expenditure requirements and
the asset base.'
Southern Electric, which serves south-east England, was one of the few
companies thought to have come out well by virtually all analysts. Other
companies which saw relatively high rises in share prices included London
Electricity.
Shares in London Electricity have performed relatively poorly in recent
months because of fears that the regulator would not approve its explanation
that its cost base is higher than most as a result of being based in the
capital.
Several analysts said that its appearance among the six companies which have
to cut price caps by 14 per cent next April meant that the regulator had
accepted London's arguments.
