<HEADLINE>
FT  12 AUG 94 / Waldegrave to argue for fish compensation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr William Waldegrave, agriculture minister, yesterday said that the
government would consider compensating Cornish fishermen whose nets had been
cut by their Spanish rivals.
The agriculture minister said that the government would take up the issue of
compensation for the fishermen with the Spanish government and that the door
for interim compensation by the British government 'was not entirely
closed'.
Meeting Cornish fishing representatives, he stressed that the Royal Navy was
present in the Bay of Biscay to protect British boats from the actions of
Spanish fishermen.
He said: 'I emphasised that the first duty of the navy and the government is
to ensure that our fishermen are not driven from the fishing grounds by
harassment or illegal action of any kind.'
The Cornish fishermen had earlier complained about being harassed by British
navy inspectors over the size of their drift nets. Spanish fishermen say
that the British are using nets which are longer than the legal limit.
Mr Paul Tyler, Liberal Democrat MP for Cornwall North, said Mr Waldegrave
was in effect admitting that the system for enforcing the European Union
rules on net size had not worked properly and that the fishermen had a
justifiable concern.
The navy has so far sent two British trawlers back to port for allegedly
fishing with nets longer than the legal limit. Mr Waldegrave said yesterday
that the government had decided not to take legal action against either of
those boats and that one of them, the Charisma, had received a caution.
Mr Waldegrave said he had tried hard to clear up 'misunderstandings' between
the navy and trawlers over measuring nets. Fishermen will now have their
nets measured on-shore before they set sail. They will then let them out at
sea in the presence of navy and EU inspectors who will be briefed on the
measurements.
'If the inspector knows what he's expecting to find, it will make it
easier,' Mr Waldegrave said.
He stressed that he would consider interim compensation although this would
be an unprecedented and difficult action.
'It is the Spanish who should pay for illegal actions against our ships,' he
said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
